<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD1C8083EEEE57C6F2D9A5F" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EEEE57C6F409A0F" blockId="5.[174,569,527,554]" box="[174,569,527,554]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
<heading id="D09E8188FFD1C8083EEEE57C6F409A0F" box="[174,569,527,554]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="4C694D67FFD1C8083EEEE57C6F409A0F" authority="(Linnaeus, 1767)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1767" box="[174,569,527,554]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Dysgonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="algira">
<emphasis id="B91DEAF6FFD1C8083EEEE57C6C149A0F" bold="true" box="[174,365,527,554]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">Dysgonia algira</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1767)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E5336F2D9A5F" blockId="5.[174,1232,575,826]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083CC0E54C6FB49A7F" box="[640,717,575,602]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[166,1225,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 19, 20 — Euclidia glyphica; 21–24 — Dysgonia algira. Scale bars: 19, 22–24 — 10 µm; 20 — 1 µm; 21 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453444/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 21</figureCitation>
), height 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD1C8083D76E54C6EBC9A7F" box="[822,965,575,602]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.7">0.7–0.8 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD1C8083A03E54C69A99A7F" box="[1091,1232,575,602]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" unit="mm" value="0.85" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.8">0.8–0.9 mm</quantity>
(n = 2). Chorion white, transparent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD1C8083EA3E50C697B9B1F" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E50C697B9B1F" blockId="5.[174,1232,575,826]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surface. Micropylar area represented by rosette and 5 rows polygonal cells (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083FBCE5EC6F339A9F" box="[508,586,671,698]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[166,1225,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 19, 20 — Euclidia glyphica; 21–24 — Dysgonia algira. Scale bars: 19, 22–24 — 10 µm; 20 — 1 µm; 21 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453444/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Rosette with 9-10 broad and short petalled cells and 5 micropylar openings, which located as star (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083C99E5CC6E509AFF" box="[729,809,703,730]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[166,1225,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 19, 20 — Euclidia glyphica; 21–24 — Dysgonia algira. Scale bars: 19, 22–24 — 10 µm; 20 — 1 µm; 21 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453444/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 24</figureCitation>
). The clear transition between cells of micropylar area and remaining egg surface absent (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083D04E5AC6EED9ADF" box="[836,916,735,762]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[166,1225,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 19, 20 — Euclidia glyphica; 21–24 — Dysgonia algira. Scale bars: 19, 22–24 — 10 µm; 20 — 1 µm; 21 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453444/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 22</figureCitation>
). There are 34–37 slightly wavy, narrow longitudinal ridges with aeropyles at walls junctions. Transverse walls narrow and distinct as ridges. Chorion sharply pebbled everywhere (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083DE8E46C6E8C9B1F" box="[936,1013,799,826]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[166,1225,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 19, 20 — Euclidia glyphica; 21–24 — Dysgonia algira. Scale bars: 19, 22–24 — 10 µm; 20 — 1 µm; 21 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453444/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
